    <section>
      <h2>Why Kittery?</h2>
      <p>Kittery is Maine's southernmost coastal town, sitting directly across the Piscataqua River from Portsmouth, New Hampshire. About 10,000 people live here year-round, but the town's economic geography extends far beyond its borders. Kittery sits at the intersection of I-95, US Route 1, and the Maine Turnpike, making it the first Maine exit for thousands of New Hampshire residents heading south.</p>
      <p>The town has two distinct economic identities. The first is residential — a quiet seaside community with working waterfront, historic neighborhoods, and a year-round population that values local businesses. The second is commercial — anchored by the famous Kittery Outlets, which draw an estimated 4-5 million visitors annually, and the associated restaurant and hospitality economy that serves those shoppers.</p>
      <p>This combination creates a market unlike almost any other in Maine. During summer weekends, Kittery's population effectively multiplies by 10-20x as tourists and New Hampshire day-trippers flood the outlet district. Even in winter, the outlet traffic continues — shoppers from New Hampshire and beyond make the trip year-round, though at lower volumes than summer.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="The New Hampshire Advantage" type="info">
      New Hampshire has not legalized recreational cannabis. NH residents who want legal cannabis must cross into Maine or make the longer trip to Massachusetts. Kittery is the closest Maine dispensary for most of southern New Hampshire — particularly the Seacoast region including Portsmouth, Dover, Rochester, and the coast down to the Massachusetts border. This is a built-in customer base that does not exist for most other Maine dispensary towns. The NH market is significant: approximately 1.3 million people live within 30 minutes of the Kittery border, none of whom can purchase legal cannabis in their home state.
    </Callout>

