    <section>
      <h2>The NH Edge: Your Biggest Opportunity</h2>
      <p>Kittery sits at the intersection of Maine and New Hampshire. This is not a marketing tagline — it is the fundamental competitive advantage of this market. New Hampshire has not legalized recreational cannabis, and shows no immediate signs of doing so. New Hampshire residents who want legal cannabis must cross the border into Maine or make a significantly longer trip to Massachusetts.</p>
      <p>Kittery is the first Maine town drivers hit after crossing the Piscataqua River bridges from Portsmouth. That geography is a competitive moat. No other Maine location serves this NH customer segment as directly. Driving from Portsmouth, NH to Kittery, ME takes approximately 10 minutes. Driving from Portsmouth to Portland takes 50 minutes. The difference is not subtle.</p>
      <p>The NH customer is qualitatively different from the Maine tourist. NH residents are making a deliberate, planned trip for a specific purpose. They have decided in advance to purchase cannabis, budgeted for it, and allocated time to make the drive. This means higher purchase intent, larger basket sizes, and more brand loyalty than impulse visitors.</p>
      <p>Position your dispensary as the convenient, trustworthy option for NH residents. Emphasize compliance, safety, and product quality in your marketing. NH customers are making a deliberate trip. They will drive past closer Maine options to reach a dispensary they trust. Once you earn that trust, the geographic advantage keeps them coming back.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Kittery Tourism Economy</h2>
      <p>Beyond the NH cross-border market, Kittery's tourism economy adds a second customer segment that amplifies the opportunity. The Kittery Outlets anchor a retail tourism industry that brings 4-5 million visitors annually. These shoppers come from across New England and beyond, many from states where cannabis is not yet legal. They represent an additional pool of potential customers who happened to be in Kittery shopping for shoes or kitchenware.</p>
      <p>The outlet shopping demographic skews toward higher incomes than the general Maine population. Outlet mall shoppers tend to be suburban families with disposable income — a commercially valuable demographic. When these shoppers see a dispensary while hunting for bargains, the impulse purchase kicks in. Dispensaries in high-visibility locations near the outlets benefit from this walk-in traffic that requires no marketing spend to capture.</p>
      <p>The seasonal pattern of tourism in Kittery differs from a beach destination like Old Orchard Beach. Outlet shopping is a year-round activity, though May through October sees higher volumes. Winter weekends still bring solid traffic from New Hampshire day-trippers avoiding the summer crowds. This makes Kittery more resilient to seasonal troughs than purely tourist-dependent markets.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Local Rules and Licensing</h2>
      <p>Kittery operates under Maine's adult-use cannabis framework, requiring both a state OCP Adult-Use Retail License and local approval from the Town of Kittery. The local approval process involves review by the Planning Board and ultimately the Town Council, depending on the zoning district and whether any variances are needed.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>State License:</strong> OCP Adult-Use Retail License from Maine's Office of Cannabis Policy</li>
        <li><strong>Local Approval:</strong> Local marijuana retail permit from Kittery Town Council or Planning Board</li>
        <li><strong>Local Annual Fee:</strong> $2,500 paid to the Town of Kittery</li>
        <li><strong>School Buffer:</strong> 500-foot minimum from schools, measured property line to property line</li>
        <li><strong>Zoning:</strong> Commercial and Gateway districts — residential zones explicitly prohibited</li>
        <li><strong>Security:</strong> Must meet Maine OCP requirements including 24-hour surveillance and access-controlled storage</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Kittery has historically been cautious but not hostile toward cannabis businesses. The town's approval timeline typically runs 60-90 days after complete application submission. Operators should begin both the state and local processes simultaneously, but avoid signing any commercial lease until preliminary local approval is secured in writing.</p>
    </section>

