    <section>
      <h2>Real Estate Considerations</h2>
      <p>Kittery has three main commercial corridors with distinct characteristics. Route 1 (the Bypass) runs parallel to I-95 and hosts most of the big-box retail, including the outlet complex. This is where outlet shoppers first enter Kittery from the north. Old Eliot Road serves the local population near the older residential areas and connects to the waterfront. Downtown Kittery is smaller but attracts visitors interested in the historic waterfront, local restaurants, and specialty shops.</p>
      <p>Square footage for a dispensary typically runs 1,200-1,800 square feet, including the sales floor, budroom, security vault, and storage. In Kittery, expect to pay $16-22 per square foot annually for commercial space on the Bypass. A 1,500 square foot space on the Bypass runs approximately $27,000-33,000 annually in rent. Sublease opportunities occasionally appear in existing shopping centers, which can reduce upfront buildout costs significantly compared to a ground-up tenant improvement.</p>
      <p>The 500-foot school buffer affects several commercially zoned parcels, particularly near the Marshwood schools to the north and the elementary school on Route 236. The densest concentration of outlet retail on the Bypass is generally outside these buffer zones, but your zoning attorney should verify any specific address against school district maps before committing. The Town of Kittery's Code Enforcement Office can provide official buffer zone documentation.</p>
      <p>NH-focused operators should note that visibility from I-95 southbound is particularly valuable. NH residents crossing the border see southbound traffic signage first. A dispensary with strong southbound I-95 visibility captures the NH customer before they enter the outlet district and potentially get distracted by shopping.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Operators Report</h2>
      <p>Kittery dispensary operators consistently report two distinct customer segments with different behaviors and value profiles.</p>
      <p>The first is NH cross-border traffic. These customers often spend more per visit than locals because they are making a deliberate trip with planned purchasing in mind. NH customers tend to buy larger quantities per visit, stock up on concentrates and edibles, and show more brand loyalty once they find a dispensary they trust. The round-trip drive of 20-60 minutes means these customers want to maximize each trip rather than make frequent small purchases.</p>
      <p>The second segment is the tourist impulse buyer. Outlet shoppers who did not plan to visit a dispensary but noticed one while shopping. This segment represents lower per-visit revenue but higher volume during peak tourism season. These customers respond to ground-floor visibility, clear signage, and a professional appearance that signals legitimacy.</p>
      <p>Marketing works differently in Kittery than in inland Maine. Your best marketing is visibility from Route 1 and I-95. A prominent sign visible from the highway does more for your business than any digital ad spend in this market. NH-focused advertising on Google Maps and search can be particularly effective since you are solving a specific, underserved need for a defined population searching for the closest legal option.</p>
    </section>

